{
  "analysis": "We are in /app with no prior command output shown. The task is to implement a MIPS interpreter in Node (vm.js) that can execute the provided MIPS ELF binary (/app/doomgeneric_mips), handle required system calls, and save rendered frames one at a time as the program runs. We need to inspect the filesystem to see the provided binary and the doomgeneric/ source, understand how frames are expected to be output, and identify the syscall and instruction coverage we must implement. We'll likely need to parse the ELF, load PT_LOAD segments into a virtual memory model, implement a subset of MIPS32 instruction decoding/execution (the subset used by the program), and handle Linux MIPS O32 syscalls (open/read/write/close, mmap/brk, exit, gettimeofday, nanosleep, etc.). We'll also want to determine the binary's endianness and ABI using file or readelf. Once we understand how frames are produced in doomgeneric (e.g., writing PPM frames to stdout or files), we can implement syscall handling to capture and save them.",
  "plan": "1) Explore /app: list files to confirm doomgeneric_mips and doomgeneric/ presence. 2) Use `file` to inspect doomgeneric_mips (endianness, ABI, static vs dynamic). 3) Peek into doomgeneric/ to understand rendering output expectations (whether frames are written to a file/stdout or via some callback). 4) Create vm.js and implement: a) ELF loader to read headers and program headers, map segments into a sparse memory model; b) MIPS32 instruction decoder for common instructions (R/I/J types: add, addu, sub, slt, and/or/xor/nor, sll/srl/sra, mult/mflo/mfhi, lb/lbu/lh/lhu/lw/sb/sh/sw, lui, ori/andi/xori/addiu, beq/bne/bgez/bltz/beqz/bnez, j/jal/jr/jalr, syscall); c) Register file with 32 registers plus hi/lo and PC, conforming to MIPS conventions; d) Endianness handling; e) Basic exception handling for syscall instruction. 5) Implement syscall handling for relevant Linux MIPS O32 syscalls: write, open/openat, read, close, fstat, brk, mmap2/mmap, munmap, mprotect (stub), exit, gettimeofday/clock_gettime, nanosleep/usleep, ioctl (stub expected), poll/select (stub), rt_sigaction/sigprocmask (stub), prlimit (stub), getpid, uname, access, stat, lseek, dup, etc. For many we can minimally implement or return plausible values, focusing primarily on those used by a statically linked DoomGeneric. 6) Implement a simple VFS mapping into host filesystem via Node fs to let the program read/write files. Create an output directory and intercept writes to known paths or detect PPM headers in write() buffers to save frames incrementally (e.g., if DoomGeneric writes PPM frames to stdout). 7) Run node vm.js, debug crashes by inspecting missing instructions/syscalls, iteratively add what's needed until the first frame is saved. We start by inspecting binaries and sources.",
